    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Right, the technical explanation. No more tales of mischievous little goblins pilfering shiny things, I promise. *Deep breath.*\n\nI was explaining why adjusting the **Cost of Goods Sold (COGS)** is generally considered the cleaner, more direct method for calculating the *true* efficiency of your inventory turnover.\n\nWhen you adjust the COGS, you are directly correcting the *expense* side of the equation. Shrinkage represents a loss—a cost that was incurred but not accounted for in sales revenue. By subtracting the value of the lost goods from COGS, you are accurately reflecting the *actual* cost of the goods that successfully moved through your system. This gives you a more honest picture of how efficiently your *usable* stock is turning over.\n\nIf you adjust the **Average Inventory** (the denominator), you are essentially saying that the inventory you *thought* you had at the end was artificially inflated by the missing stock. While mathematically possible, this can sometimes distort the relationship between the cost of goods sold and the average stock level in a way that is harder to interpret for management. It muddies the waters, much like trying to herd a swarm of tiny, chaotic goblins into a neat little line.",
